<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Service (1995 through 1999) - SECTION 7: VIBRATION DAMPER, CRANKSHAFT, MAIN
        BEARINGS, FLYWHEEL AND CRANKCASE - CRANKSHAFT AND MAIN BEARINGS
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>CRANKSHAFT AND MAIN BEARINGS</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="6">
            <title>REMOVAL</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rotate the engine stand so the crankshaft is facing horizontal.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Prior to bearing cap removal, check to see that caps and crankcase are stamped to identify
                            location. If they are not marked, stamp in numerical order 1-7, starting with No.1 at the
                            front of the engine. Stamp the crankcase oil pan rail and main bearing caps on the camshaft
                            side. Refer to Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600765">7.65</hotlnk>.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the six (6) main bearing caps as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Loosen main bearing cap bolts (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600766">7.66</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1600764" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg6895" filename="../figeg6/eg6895.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7.64 Removing Oil Pick-up Tube Support Bracket</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1600765" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11616" filename="../figcg1/cg11616.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7.65 Main Bearing Cap Locations</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1600766" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg6898" filename="../figeg6/eg6898.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7.66 Removing Main Bearing Cap</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Grasp bolts and rock main bearing cap back and forth to loosen and remove cap (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600767">7.67</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove lower bearing shell from main bearing cap and keep in order with bearing cap
                        for inspection.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove No. 7 (rear) thrust bearing as follows (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600768">7.68</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ):
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Loosen two (2) rear thrust bearing mounting bolts.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Insert a flat blade screwdriver between bearing cap and crankcase wall. Twist the
                        screwdriver and walk bearing cap up. Alternate from side to side of the bearing cap with each
                        twist of the screwdriver.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>ONLY USE HAND PRESSURE WHEN TWISTING THE SCREWDRIVER.</para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove bearing cap.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove crankshaft from the crankcase using an appropriate lifting sling, as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600769">7.69</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>BE CAREFUL NOT TO DAMAGE THE CRANKSHAFT WHEN REMOVED.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef1600767" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5354" filename="../figeg5/eg5354.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.67 Removing Main Bearing Cap</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600768" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5358" filename="../figeg5/eg5358.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.68 Removing Rear Thrust Bearing</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600769" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5359" filename="../figeg5/eg5359.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7.69 Removing Crankshaft</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove upper main bearing shells by pushing them out of main bearing saddle with your
                    thumbs as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk document="e160_197.xml" xrefid="ef1600770">7.70</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . Mark the upper shells and put with lower shells until a proper inspection can be done.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
